com.github.dm.jrt.core.channel

Interface Channel<IN,OUT>

  • Type Parameters:
    IN - the input data type.
    OUT - the output data type.
    All Superinterfaces:
    Iterable<OUT>, Iterator<OUT>

    public interface Channel<IN,OUT>
extends Iterator<OUT>, Iterable<OUT>
    Interface defining the basic communication channel with the routine invocation.

    Channel instances are used to transfer data to and from the code executed inside the routine invocation.

    Created by davide-maestroni on 09/09/2014.

    • Method Detail

      • abort

        boolean abort()
        Closes the channel and abort the transfer of data, thus aborting the routine invocation.
        An instance of AbortException will be passed as the abortion reason.
        If a delay has been set through the dedicated methods, the abortion will be accordingly postponed.

        Note that, in case the channel is already closed, the method invocation will have no effect.

        Returns:
        whether the channel status changed as a result of the call.
        See Also:
        after(DurationMeasure), after(long, TimeUnit), afterNoDelay()

      • abort

        boolean abort(@Nullable
              Throwable reason)
        Closes the channel and abort the transfer of data, thus aborting the routine invocation and causing the specified throwable to be passed as the abortion reason.
        The throwable, unless it extends the base RoutineException, will be wrapped as the cause of an AbortException instance.
        If a delay has been set through the dedicated methods, the abortion will be accordingly postponed.

        Note that, in case the channel is already closed, the method invocation will have no effect.

        Parameters:
        reason - the throwable object identifying the reason of the invocation abortion.
        Returns:
        whether the channel status changed as a result of the call.
        See Also:
        after(DurationMeasure), after(long, TimeUnit), afterNoDelay()

      • after

        @NotNull
Channel<IN,OUT> after(long delay,
                               @NotNull
                               TimeUnit timeUnit)
        Tells the channel to delay the following operations of the specified time duration.
        Read operations will not be affected.

        By default the delay is set to 0.

        Note that closing and abortion commands will be delayed as well. Note, however, that a delayed abortion will not prevent the invocation from completing, as pending input data do.

        Note that the implementing class should ensure that calls of this method from different threads will not interfere with each others.

        Parameters:
        delay - the delay value.
        timeUnit - the delay time unit.
        Returns:
        this channel.
        Throws:
        RoutineException - if the execution has been aborted.
        IllegalArgumentException - if the specified delay is negative.

      • all

        @NotNull
List<OUT> all()
        Consumes all the results by waiting for the routine to complete at the maximum for the set delay.

        Note that this method invocation will block the calling thread until the routine invocation completes or is aborted, or the timeout elapses.

        Returns:
        the list of results.
        Throws:
        OutputTimeoutException - if the channel is set to throw an exception when the timeout elapses.
        RoutineException - if the execution has been aborted.
        IllegalStateException - if this channel is already bound to a consumer or another channel.

        @NotNull
<AFTER> Channel<? super OUT,AFTER> bind(@NotNull

        Binds this channel to the specified one.
        After method exits, all the output will be passed only to the specified input channel. Attempting to read through the dedicated methods will cause an IllegalStateException to be thrown.

      • bind

        @NotNull
Channel<IN,OUT> bind(@NotNull
                              ChannelConsumer<? super OUT> consumer)
        Binds this channel to the specified consumer.
        After method exits, all the output will be passed only to the consumer. Attempting to read through the dedicated methods will cause an IllegalStateException to be thrown.
        If a delay has been set through the dedicated methods, the transfer of data will be accordingly postponed.

        Note that the consumer methods may be called on the runner thread.

        Parameters:
        consumer - the consumer instance.
        Returns:
        this channel.
        Throws:
        IllegalStateException - if this channel is already bound.
        See Also:
        after(DurationMeasure), after(long, TimeUnit), afterNoDelay()

      • close

        @NotNull
Channel<IN,OUT> close()
        Closes this channel and completes the invocation.
        After channel is closed, attempting to pass additional input data through the dedicated methods will cause an IllegalStateException to be thrown.
        If a delay has been set through the dedicated methods, the closing command will be accordingly postponed.

        Note that, even if calling this method is not strictly mandatory, some invocation implementations may rely on the completion notification to produce their results. So, it's always advisable to close the channel as soon as all the input data has been passed.

        Returns:
        this channel.
        See Also:
        after(DurationMeasure), after(long, TimeUnit), afterNoDelay()

        OUT nextOrElse(OUT output)
        Consumes the first available result by waiting at the maximum for the set delay.
        If the timeout elapses and the channel is not configured to throw an exception or abort the invocation, the specified alternative output is returned.

        Note that this method invocation will block the calling thread until a new output is available, the routine invocation completes or is aborted, or the timeout elapses.

        Parameters:

      • unsorted

        @NotNull
Channel<IN,OUT> unsorted()
        Tells the channel to not sort the passed input data.

        Note that only the inputs passed with a 0 delay will be delivered in the same order as they are passed to the channel, while the others will be delivered as soon as the dedicated runner handles the specific execution.

        This is the default behavior.

        Note that the implementing class should ensure that calls of this method from different threads will not interfere with each others.

        Returns:
        this channel.
        Throws:
        RoutineException - if the execution has been aborted.
        See Also:
        sorted()
